@Vaer
I just realized that I accidentally started reading comments from newest, so i'm just seeing this now and I've mentioned it a few times already. Of course you beat me to it. Can I mention that it was produced by ENO?

I re-watched the performance in STOP MAKING SENSE and now I need a nap. That tour was amazing (saw it at the Greek in Berkeley) and it really is one of the best concert movies ever made.

@Doug
SchMEAR, whether noun or verb, has a certain gusto and brio that is completely absent from the pallid, anemic SMEAR.
You might as well have a pastrami on Wonderbread with mayo. Yeesh!

@SP
I was introduced to Mel with Springtime for H---- (probably an emu embargoed name) at about 10 years old. A lot probably went over my head, but catchy tune.
My parents weren't the type to buy comedy records so I was very late to that party.

@Dan
I saw this documentary about Hedy Lamar on PBS American Experience a while ago. It's called "Bombshell: The Hedy Lamar Story." I believe her inventions contributed to the basis for computers.

<a href="https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6752848" target="_blank">https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6752848</a>/

@SP

I, too, thought of how apropos that silly conjecture was as I was thinking I was going to blue star a Monday.  Would have served me right.

CBGB was a complete mystery to me.

@Jan
Interesting, I had never thought of that.  Hot oil, with nothing in it,  doesn't sizzle.
However, the fat in a slice of bacon is a tissue, which contains both fats and water (and protein, etc), so it seems correct to say that the fat sizzles when heated.

@Seth A

Actually, so few people even acquaint the rhyme with its original wording that I think bringing it up does more harm than good. I never heard that wording actually used and that goes back 60 years, and only heard about it in these comments. In my opinion (admittedly not as a person of color) this rhyme has passed out of the realm of being remotely racist. I suppose to be safe we could clue it as “tiny”.

It’s like “ring around the Rosie” I suppose we could ban it from preschools because it was originally about the Black Plague, but why bother?

@SP
The Plague connection is probably a myth. The rhyme was known before that, according to historians.
I remember the change to 'tiger' - I was about age 6.

@Vaer
I don't know if you'll see this, so I'll likely post it again later, in the Wordplay comments for Wednesdays puzzle. 

I don't know why it would have said NJ in 2016. For several years, beginning in 2004, I was back and forth between NJ and Vegas, not exactly as a snowbird, just three months at a time in each place. But I became a permanent resident of Vegas in 2007. Strange.

