@CrispyShot

I can't believe you didn't suddenly veer off for an epic road journey that would surely change your life forever! Or ending up sailing off of a cliff, followed by the coppers, and ending in certain doom. Either way, adventures galore, life changed forever!!  😏

But seriously, folks, thanks for sharing the correct pronunciation. I said it, mostly in my mind, as you did. Good to know!!

@CrispyShot
love this. I have a lot of family in the area including Framingham, so I've known the pronunciation since childhood, long before i associated it with crossworld. 

My family keeps a list of words we first encountered in print and then mispronounced when we tried to use them in conversation--calliope, haphazard, etc.   There are a lot of geographic names in there,including Mojave and Puerto Rico.

@CrispyShot
one more thing. Driving in MA did you encounter "Entering [town name]" signs? I had the pleasure of working on a show which featured the song "Entering Marion" by John Forster. you're welcome.

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_Lw8ADKeaOM" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_Lw8ADKeaOM</a>

@Josh T
Sound of Music is a classic that is  broadcast on TV at least once a year. That said, I'm willing to concede that if a person
had only heard the word ROUE in the song lyrics, they wouldn't necessarily know how it's spelled. I knew the word from elsewhere.

@Josh T
Gender divide at work? I can't count the number of books in which someone is described as 'an aging roué'. Usually pathetic, sometimes evil, but a repeated type. A quick search produced everything from the 1924 film 'Sinners in Silk' starring Adolphe Menjou to a 2007 blog here: <a href="https://althouse.blogspot.com/2007/05/aging-rou-who-is-almost-too-facile-and.html?m=1" target="_blank">https://althouse.blogspot.com/2007/05/aging-rou-who-is-almost-too-facile-and.html?m=1</a>
As the saying goes, "Not dead yet!"

@Grant

Can we be friends if I promise to learn about both of them?
Actually turns out Neal and I are both Boston University alums and overlapped—he graduated in 1981 and I in 1984.

@Joe
every single one of my "best" times is suspect. I find the stats useful as a gauge that I am indeed improving, but all must be taken with a grain of salt.

There *are* people who can correct errors. it helps to have proof such as screenshots. I hear that sometimes they'll take your word, sometimes not.

@Barry Ancona

The "and vans" threw me, personally. While GMC may be commonly associated with pickups, I for one do not normally link them to vans. Had the clue just been "big inits. in pickup trucks" I think it would've been a bit clearer.

Even still, GMC is generally not the first maker that comes to mind for most Americans and pickup trucks--Ford, Chevrolet, Dodge, and even Toyota all came to mind first before I ever landed on GMC.

@Edward
I too would think of other truck manufacturers first, which is perhaps an argument for including "and vans" in the clue. Also it does say "initials" and none of those four companies  you mentioned is known by initials, unless you resort to the old joke Fix Or Repair Daily, and that was one letter too long.

I'll grant you it was one of a few crosses I thought unusually crunchy for a Monday. xwstats agrees, rating it "hard".

