@D
you're mistaken. commenters often point out what they considered bad clues.

they hate it when you don't mention which clues you thought were bad.

@D
you too are mistaken. believe me I'm not unaware of your comments. You often find snark where I see none. (I admit sometimes there's snark, which I don't love). When someone points out what they consider to be a bad clue it opens a dialog; often the veterans will point out that ETUI  and AERIE and OTT are glue that is likely to reappear so you should maybe memorize them. I cannot remember a single instance of someone saying the fifth entry in the dictionary was incredibly well known. "Bad clueing" and "Terrible puzzle" don't allow for a dialog, and they don't allow any of us to learn anything. It's interesting to have the opportunity to see things from the perspective of someone who is just starting to learn how to solve the NYT crossword. I wish we could all try to learn from one another without being either snarky or dismissive. 

Tomorrow will bring another puzzle. Let's see what we can learn from  it.
